english:
  title: Colophon to the New Woodblock Edition of the Eastern Slope Collected Works, Commissioned by the Prefect of Jeonju
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Collections of writings circulate through the world according to the tastes of each age. Yet since ancient times, none has flourished as widely or been cherished as dearly as the Eastern Slope's works. Is it not because his prose brims with richness, his allusions span vast learning, and the nourishment of his art flows endlessly to readers without depletion? From high officials to young scholars newly arrived, none have ever let his pages rest in their hands for even a moment. All who savor the lingering fragrance of his words seek to imitate them.

    The woodblocks once existed in Sangju, but were tragically consumed by barbarian flames, leaving not a single copy. The Prefect of Wansan, Minister Choi Chi of the Ministry of Rites, a gentleman devoted to learning and fond of virtue, heard of this loss and sighed deeply. He resolved to undertake a new carving. Yet those were perilous times—barbarian cavalry came and went like lightning, leaving no moment for peace. The prefecture remained in turmoil, with scarce a tranquil year. It seemed there would be no leisure for such scholarly pursuits.

    But the Prefect declared: "The ancients sang songs even amidst warfare and lectured on the arts while still bearing arms. The written word cannot be abandoned. This is but a small task for so great a prefecture—surely it can be accomplished in a moment. Should we delay merely because of these small barbarian troubles and wait for times of peace, will not our successors also delay, and so my ambition never be fulfilled?" Thus he made his decision and submitted his report to the throne. The sovereign, himself a lover of letters, readily granted approval.

    Taking advantage of the intervals when the raiders had not come and the farming season was slack, the Prefect had the blocks carved. In mere days the work was complete. The expense was modest and the labor abundant. Truly, only one whose grip on affairs is firm and righteous, whose reserves are inexhaustible, could accomplish such a great deed with such swiftness in such dark times. By this, one may discern the very essence of his governance.

    Since the Prefect is my disciple, he asked me to record this account. I deeply admired how he transformed the loss of books from another district into a personal concern, and redirected that sorrow toward enriching his own students. Thus I have written this brief chronicle to append as a colophon.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '東坡 (Eastern Slope): A reference to Su Shi (1037-1101), the renowned Song dynasty literatus and poet, also known by this sobriquet.'
  - key: ''
    value: '完山 (Wansan): An ancient name for Jeonju (全州) in Korea.'
  - key: ''
    value: '虜兵 (Barbarian cavalry): A reference to Mongol forces conducting raids during the Goryeo period.'
  - key: ''
    value: '臨戎雅歌: An allusion to the classical ideal of maintaining cultural refinement even during military conflict.'
